	<article class="article ">
		<header class="block-content block-content-l1 block-content-center">
						<div class="block-content-header">
				<h6 class="b-content-section heading-square"><a href="/sections/essays-memoirs-true-stories">Essays, Memoirs, and True Stories</a></h6>
				<h1 class="block-content-title">Easily Led</h1>

				
				<ul class="block-content-meta list-inline-border tiny"><li>
							By <a class="meta-article-contributors" href="/contributors/gillian-kendall">Gillian Kendall</a></li><li><a href="/issues/443">November 2012</a></li></ul>

			</div>

																			

				<figure class="block-content-photo block-content-photo-large photo photo-outset-center-large">
					
					<img src="data:image/svg+xml;charset=utf-8,%3Csvg xmlns%3D'http%3A%2F%2Fwww.w3.org%2F2000%2Fsvg' viewBox%3D'0 0 1985 1960'%2F%3E"
		data-src=https://226391-691236-raikfcquaxqncofqfm.stackpathdns.com/thumbs/1180x1195r/photos/443-24-somers.jpg data-src-retina=https://226391-691236-raikfcquaxqncofqfm.stackpathdns.com/thumbs/2360x2390r/photos/443-24-somers.jpg
	 alt="443 - Somers - Kendall"
	 class="lazy">

										<figcaption>

						
																				<div class="photo-credit">
								&copy;&nbsp;<a href="/contributors/craig-somers">Craig Somers</a>
							</div>
																		</figcaption>
									</figure>

					</header>

				<div class="article-body link-text-wrap">
																		<p><span class="dropcap">&ldquo;I</span>&rsquo;ll be the one with the long white beard,&rdquo; my old boyfriend tells me. His voice on the phone is low and hesitant, but he&rsquo;s coming to pick me up right away. Thirty-five years ago he was my first lover, and I am coming back to visit him because I&rsquo;m alone in England, where he lives, and so is he. His last lady friend has meandered back to her ex, and my last lady friend broke up with me in May. I&rsquo;ve spent the summer traveling in Europe, and now, at the end, I&rsquo;ve arranged this spontaneous, short rendezvous with Nelson.</p>

<p>I refrain from telling him, <em>I&rsquo;ll be the one with thirty extra pounds</em>, but I warn him about my short hair. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m afraid you won&rsquo;t like it,&rdquo; I murmur, as coy as if we&rsquo;d just met. I know he won&rsquo;t like it: the short cut makes me look more like the middle-aged lesbian I am and even less like his teenage lover from 1976.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Walk back to the coach station,&rdquo; he tells me. &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll be there shortly, fifteen minutes at the most.&rdquo;</p>

<p>It&rsquo;s late on a chilly afternoon, and I don&rsquo;t have a sweater. Petulant, I say, &ldquo;Why don&rsquo;t you meet me here?&rdquo; I&rsquo;m calling him from a nice old pub with a small, cushy bar overlooking the river.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Just walk back across the bridge,&rdquo; Nelson repeats. &ldquo;Look for a white van.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I wait in the pub, thinking critical thoughts. Why can&rsquo;t he meet me where I&rsquo;m comfortable instead of in the stupid parking lot? When we were together, he always chose the destination for our dates, often not even telling me where we were going or why. I didn&rsquo;t question it as a teenager, but at fifty-one I am accustomed to negotiation and agreement.</p>

<p>But then I remember that this is what I came for: I want someone else to lead.</p>

<p>Over the past eighteen years I&rsquo;ve had four relationships, all with women, and most of the time I&rsquo;ve been the head cheerleader, main driving force, and primary stakeholder. Now, following my spring heartbreak, I&rsquo;m looking to bask briefly in a summer glade where I&rsquo;m pretty sure I&rsquo;ll be the brightest attraction in my companion&rsquo;s day, season, and possibly even year. This man is going to wholly admire and enjoy me, I hope, and then he&rsquo;s going to let go.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p class="dropcap">After waiting fifteen minutes and then passive-aggressively waiting five more, I cross the bridge over a river dotted with ivory-colored swans, the descendants of the swans I saw when I lived here in the seventies. Only a few cars are parked in the lot, and only one is a van. From its driver&rsquo;s side a man with glasses gets out, but he looks too old and too intellectual to be Nelson. Possibly it&rsquo;s some other aged hippie with a white beard and a white van waiting in this spot for someone else, probably someone younger and slimmer and with much longer hair.</p>

<p>But I recognize his posture: wide across the chest and square-shouldered. He stands tall and moves gracefully. As I get closer, his eyes through the new, heavy glasses show warmth and trepidation. He&rsquo;s trimmed his mustache, making it neat but askew. When he speaks, his teeth seem different too.</p>

<p>&ldquo;You&rsquo;re lookin&rsquo; good, lady.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I hug him politely, then stand back and say, &ldquo;You look different.&rdquo;</p>

<p>He gazes into the mid-distance, pretending chagrin. &ldquo;I look <em>exactly</em> the same!&rdquo; He pronounces the word with a distinct pedantic <em>t</em>, which is so unlike him that it makes me laugh.</p>

<p>&ldquo;You have new glasses,&rdquo; I say. His eyes, though, haven&rsquo;t changed.</p>

<p>&ldquo;I had to get those,&rdquo; he says comfortably. &ldquo;Eyes and ears wear out, don&rsquo;t they? I shall soon be going deaf. I shall get a <em>hearing aid</em>.&rdquo; His voice is deep and earthy; he pronounces <em>hearing aid</em> elegantly, and with horror.</p>

<p>He always talked about being old, even when he was thirty-four.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p class="dropcap">In 1976 I lied about my age to get the barmaid job at the Golden Lion. On my second day of work Nelson came striding across the pub as if it were his own living room. He looked lean and solid in his blue-gray boiler suit, with a worn, slouchy cap and a ponytail. I decided I wanted him as my first lover. He took the corner stool, faced me, and winked so fast I wasn&rsquo;t sure I&rsquo;d seen it, saying, businesslike, &ldquo;Pint of bitter, please, miss.&rdquo;</p>

<p>After the pub shut for the afternoon, as I washed up the dirties, I said to the landlady, glowing, &ldquo;I like Nelson!&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Ayeh, he&rsquo;s a character.&rdquo; She wiped a glass with an almost dry towel and then held it up to the light for inspection.</p>

<p>I stayed quiet, hoping she&rsquo;d say more. Was Nelson married? Did he have a girlfriend? Did he <em>want</em> a girlfriend?</p>

<p>And she, knowing that the answer to all those questions was yes, said again, &ldquo;He&rsquo;s a character, he is.&rdquo; She set the clean glass on the shelf with dozens of others.</p>

<p>That Friday night, Nelson came into the Golden Lion with a woman, somewhat blond but largely obscured behind her ugly metal-framed glasses. She was older than I, and her home-bleached hair wasn&rsquo;t nearly as long as mine. She wasn&rsquo;t plump like me, but there was a beer belly under her jeans, and her face had no expression. She walked in behind Nelson, furtively lighting a cigarette and standing aside as he took his place among his drunken cronies. His first order was a pint for him, a half for her, and &ldquo;One for yourself, miss?&rdquo; which meant he was offering me money to buy myself a drink. I already had plenty of drinks paid for, since that was the form that tipping took, but I accepted his coins for a half of lager, waiting to be introduced. But he didn&rsquo;t mention the woman by his side all evening. She kept close and closemouthed, and when he excused himself &ldquo;for a quick whiz,&rdquo; he lifted her hand and squeezed it.</p>

<p>When I left at 10:30 <span class="smallcaps">PM</span>, the official closing time, Nelson and the woman stayed on for the illegal after-hours session. As I swung on my green cape and slid out the side door, the landlady was drawing the curtains in the front, so no one passing by &mdash; especially not any policemen &mdash; could see in. The brewery knew, and the landlords knew, and the locals knew about the after-hours sessions, which were the most lucrative time of the day, but if the bar got caught, the fines ran to thousands of pounds.</p>

<p>Similar fines were in effect for the employment of minors, but I was tall, busty, and American, bigger in many ways than the local girls. No one ever asked for proof of age.</p>

<p>That Sunday at lunchtime the blonde with spectacles, whose name I&rsquo;d learned was Debbie, was back with Nelson again, and I guessed that they&rsquo;d spent the night together. When she ordered a half of bitter, I pulled it into an unladylike mug instead of a straight, slim glass. Handing it over, I said, &ldquo;What are you doing today?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Dunno, really,&rdquo; she said, abashed. &ldquo;Bit of washing later. Then I&rsquo;ll make us some supper.&rdquo; I moved away to serve another customer, disturbed to learn that they lived together and embarrassed for her sake that drinking at the pub and standing silently by Nelson&rsquo;s side as he flirted and told stories was the extent of her plans.</p>

