<p>In bed a few hours later, in plain view of the silk-swathed mirror, we reenact that first wonderful drama, and later, when we&rsquo;ve collapsed in each other&rsquo;s arms in the pink, mirrored swirl, I say, &ldquo;Re<em>mem</em>ber?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Oh, yes,&rdquo; he says, eyes closed, smiling. He remembers.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p class="dropcap">Sometimes, after we&rsquo;d had sex in the secret, locked room at the top of the old house, before he&rsquo;d rouse me and tell me to wash myself and get dressed because Debbie would soon be home, Nelson would lie looking at the wall, which was papered with soft-porn magazine photos and felt-tip drawings of his wife and former lovers, and I&rsquo;d ask him, &ldquo;What are you looking at?&rdquo; to find out which other woman he was contemplating.</p>

<p>After we&rsquo;d been together several months, we were lying together one afternoon and talking when he squeezed me and said, &ldquo;Ask me what you usually ask.&rdquo; He was staring at the wall.</p>

<p>&ldquo;What are you looking at?&rdquo; I responded obediently.</p>

<p>&ldquo;You.&rdquo; He pointed with his chin to a new portrait: my face beside the face of a horse, in intertwining lines of purples and blues and red and white. Both the faces were large-eyed with waving hair, and both wore matching expressions of integrity and calm intelligence.</p>

<p>I stood up, thrilled, and traced the lines with a finger.</p>

<p>&ldquo;I&rsquo;m the horse,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;And this is how I&rsquo;ll always remember you, after you go.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I cried then, because he&rsquo;d drawn us, and yet I would leave him, to go back to the U.S. for college, to go to big places and meet fascinating people and be with all the &ldquo;young studs&rdquo; he said would be lined up, snorting and pawing the ground, to seduce me.</p>

<p>&ldquo;You&rsquo;ve got a lot of people to love,&rdquo; he told me more than once. &ldquo;You&rsquo;ve got your whole life ahead of you, and your world is a whole lot bigger and brighter than this place and me.&rdquo; He knew I&rsquo;d have stayed in that small town with him forever if he&rsquo;d asked me to. He didn&rsquo;t ask.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p class="dropcap">In between bouts of sex and laughing, we talk about the possibility of Nelson&rsquo;s coming to visit me in the U.S., and he wonders if he can get a visa. It&rsquo;s been thirty years since he was last arrested, but it was for possession of firearms, a felony in England.</p>

<p>The cops had broken into his house to look for him after he&rsquo;d wrecked his truck. Drunk, he&rsquo;d walked away from the Ford and the tilting street lamp and escaped unsteadily down the path to hide in one of the places he used to take me near the river. He spent the night there, building a fire to keep warm while the police made a thorough search of every cupboard and drawer in his house. That&rsquo;s how they found the guns.</p>

<p>The following week the policemen returned with a search warrant, and they tore through his belongings again as he watched &mdash; handcuffed, sober, and livid. First they took the Winchester rifle down from over the fireplace. American, unregistered, and stolen many times, it was worth a few hundred pounds, but he used it as a decoration alongside a steer&rsquo;s horns, a Western saddle, and harness brasses.</p>

<p>Then the policemen &mdash; all younger than Nelson, who had known them since they were born &mdash; started opening doors and drawers. They found handguns and switchblades and no licenses, locks, or receipts.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Hell,&rdquo; he tells me, laughing, &ldquo;there was thousands of quid worth of stuff I&rsquo;d forgot I had.&rdquo;</p>

<p>The youngest cop forced open a hidden drawer inside a cabinet and withdrew a large pistol. Nelson told him it was a replica, but the cop said it looked real to him. Nelson still seems proud of what he said next: &ldquo;Oh, right, I forgot I was talking to a policeman. <em>Replica</em> is a big word that means it looks like the genuine article.&rdquo;</p>

<p>The cop smashed the gun into Nelson&rsquo;s mouth. Heavy, solid, and not a replica, it broke a tooth. Then they took him to jail, and now he&rsquo;s not sure about a visa.</p>

<p>As he tells the story, I&rsquo;m sitting on the leather couch, nestling my feet in his lap. &ldquo;You didn&rsquo;t have guns when I knew you, did you?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yes, I always traded in guns,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;They&rsquo;re valuable and easy to hide.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Wait, what?&rdquo; I reach out and touch his arm. &ldquo;When we were together? In the other house?&rdquo; The 150-year-old flint-brick house where, in our special bed in the secret room, he took my virginity as gently as he could? In <em>that</em> house he stored firearms?</p>

<p>He takes my offered hand without comment, and his touch feels so warm I can barely think. &ldquo;That house was fulla guns.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I&rsquo;m excited and silenced by the image of my virginal self being seduced while, a foot away from my tousled hair, my lover hid a fortune in illegal weaponry. Somehow this makes me feel valuable and precious, like one of his secret treasures.</p>

<p>After he says &ldquo;fulla guns&rdquo; in that factual, unimpressed way, I slither along the settee until I&rsquo;m right next to him, bewildered and aroused. &ldquo;So, you had the guns just to sell, to make money, not for self-protection?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;No, I had them for self-protection too. But I never shot anyone with them.&rdquo; I take a slow breath before he adds, &ldquo;I shot <em>at</em> people, but I&rsquo;ve got bad aim. Never hit anyone.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p class="dropcap">The last time we make love, the Tuesday I have to leave, I&rsquo;m not wet, but I welcome him in anyway. His penis feels especially stiff and large. It&rsquo;s painful at first, and my breath escapes in jagged, rhythmic response.</p>

<p>A few hours later, traveling alone toward London, I sit high in the train car with my forehead pressed against the window, reviewing every memory of our forty hours together. Sometimes I sigh, and sometimes I feel physical contractions in my body, as well as a metaphysical expansion. The center of me misses the center of him. In London I ride the top of England&rsquo;s red buses and walk lightly through the wet gray world, feeling voluptuous and giddy. From the train station I mail Nelson a postcard, saying, &ldquo;I feel I&rsquo;ve been forever changed.&rdquo; I think at first that it is just new-old love, but my face reflected in the rain-dark window glows, as if I&rsquo;ve received an infusion of moonlight beneath my skin.</p>

<p>Even as I travel away from him, I am everywhere and all the time in a bubble of joy, radiating &mdash; I can tell by the way people look at me &mdash; something that everyone wants. All the next week, as I visit my brother and prepare to go back to the U.S., strangers keep talking to me, offering me cups of tea and their life stories. Men especially smile at me, sit nearby, and start conversations. It&rsquo;s like being sixteen again, a long-haired, large-eyed newcomer, only this time I understand that it isn&rsquo;t me they&rsquo;re seeing. It isn&rsquo;t the hot pull of sex, either; it&rsquo;s something grander, more transparent.</p>

<p>As I savor the memories of our two days and nights together, I keep coming back to the moment when Nelson and I were looking into each other&rsquo;s eyes while making love. Realizing what this means, I call him from a pay phone and say, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m in love!&rdquo;</p>

<p>He sounds joyful. &ldquo;Yeah, in love with life! You go around smiling at everyone, and they all think you&rsquo;re mad.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;No,&rdquo; I say. &ldquo;With you.&rdquo; There is a strange dip in my voice.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yeah?&rdquo; He seems dubious. Slowly he adds, &ldquo;I think we could safely say I reciprocate the sentiment.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;I&rsquo;m like a sixteen-year-old!&rdquo; I burst out, like a sixteen-year-old.</p>

<p>&ldquo;That will fade,&rdquo; he says, like a sixty-eight-year-old.</p>

<p>But my misty-eyed afterglow doesn&rsquo;t evaporate; it thickens. Euphoria sets in. I cradle my sister-in-law&rsquo;s cats like newborns and tell my impossible brother that I love him. I beam at shopkeepers and feel wildly alive.</p>

<p>Going back to the U.S., I don&rsquo;t know when or even if I&rsquo;ll see Nelson again. Maybe the distance and time will put things in perspective; maybe he&rsquo;ll fly over to be with me; maybe I&rsquo;ll come back. There are many maybes.</p>

<p>Sometime early in our reunion, after he came inside me, Nelson lay down and said with wonder, &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve never felt that way with anyone, ever.&rdquo; I felt awed too, by the force we&rsquo;d unearthed or re-created. There wasn&rsquo;t time to consider or contemplate; we were too busy enjoying it.</p>

<p>After I&rsquo;m home, I talk with my best friend about what drew me back to Nelson. And she, who met him in the 1970s and who knows my heart better than I do, suggests that I am trying to heal something from my past: At the age of sixteen, in the pitiful, predictable way of many daughters who feel rejected by their fathers, I had sought out a relationship with an unavailable older man, as if I could make up for growing up without paternal love. But, also predictably, I couldn&rsquo;t. And, my friend thinks, at the age of fifty-one I went back to try again.</p>

<p>Denial of my friend&rsquo;s facile psychology rises up in me &mdash; so fast that I know she&rsquo;s right. But she&rsquo;s also wrong, because the thing is, my unconscious plan <em>worked</em>. What I felt from and for Nelson was unfettered, undemanding, happy appreciation. Without Debbie, without the pub regulars gossiping about us, without a teenager&rsquo;s curfews and conditions, and without any commitment, we were finally free to love each other.</p>

<p>When I came to him, confused and sad from my recent breakup and shaky from months of travel, Nelson offered practical solidity in a house he&rsquo;d built by hand. He cooked eggs from his chickens and vegetables from his garden and bought cheese and bread at the market to toast for me. We ate quietly from tin plates on a table covered with the local newspaper, and when we&rsquo;d finished eating, one of us did the few dishes by hand, and then we went to the pub and came home and made love as if for the first time.</p>

<p>Nelson was my first lover, and he tells me now that I am the only woman ever to have really loved him.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p class="dropcap">Back at home, I continue calling Nelson, probably too often, and we talk about the weather and what&rsquo;s happening in the pub or growing in his garden. Once, I ask why he never rings me.</p>

<p>&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t call people!&rdquo; he protests. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s not something I do.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;You used to when I was in college.&rdquo; The phone would startle me from sleep in my little dorm bed: Nelson calling to say the sun was up and it was boo-tiful and so was I.</p>

<p>&ldquo;That was the last time I called anyone.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I laugh and ask him to write down my number in case he wants to use it, but I don&rsquo;t ask him to ring me. The only thing he asks of me is not to ask anything of him.</p>

<p>In all the time I knew Nelson, he never went to a doctor. Now he tells me he has to go every six months. &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve got some growths in the front of my head; they put a camera up my nose. And there&rsquo;s something wrong with my prostate, and it might be cancer.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Isn&rsquo;t growing old lovely?&rdquo; I say, and he laughs softly.</p>

<p>Grasping the phone tight and gesticulating with my free hand, I say, &ldquo;All that stuff &mdash; if you go deaf or you can&rsquo;t get an erection or you need a hip replacement and can&rsquo;t walk for a while &mdash; all that is <span class="smallcaps">OK</span> with me. I just want to be with you.&rdquo; I mean it vehemently, suddenly aware that at sixty-nine or seventy or beyond, he may not get a better offer, and at fifty-one or fifty-two or beyond, I might finally be his only lover.</p>

<p>He says something about my putting that in writing, then tells me that a barmaid leaned across the counter last night to give him a kiss, and he had to wipe the lipstick from his beard, and everyone in the pub had a laugh. I laugh too, but the top of my stomach caves in, and I say, &ldquo;Should I be worried?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;I like the girl!&rdquo; he says. And then he tells me about a horse he might buy.</p>

<p>Maybe in his dotage Nelson will make me the one woman he wants to be with, but by karmic rights it would be only fair if, after I&rsquo;d been living in his house long enough to feel it was my own, a younger, more confident woman bounced into his local pub, and she didn&rsquo;t know or care about his American live-in but liked Nelson and offered him something that he didn&rsquo;t even know he wanted. In a fair world I&rsquo;d come home and notice an extra coffee cup in the sink. I&rsquo;d see scratches on his back that he&rsquo;d tell me were from when he slipped and fell against a fence. When the cream-yellow rooster woke at dawn, crowing and showing off, I&rsquo;d rub open my eyes in the big, pink-curtained, mirrored bed and find that Nelson was gone, and I&rsquo;d remember: <em>He&rsquo;s easily led</em>.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p class="dropcap">When I first was separated from Nelson, at the age of seventeen, I wrote him frantically. Nearly every day for six months I&rsquo;d walk from my rented room to the Princeton public library, go upstairs to a soundproof cubicle, sit down at the humming <span class="smallcaps">IBM</span> Selectric, and set its margins to the width of a blue aerogramme. Then I&rsquo;d single-space my teenage adoration and loneliness, writing many variations of how I wished he hadn&rsquo;t let me go, and how I missed making love with him. Most of all I typed &mdash; and then repeated, longhand, above my signature of the secret name he&rsquo;d given me &mdash; that I loved him more than anything and always would, signing every letter with an effortless &ldquo;Yours forever,&rdquo; as if I could have known then what that might mean, as if I actually would continue to know him and love him for the rest of my life.</p>
														</div>


				
