			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="394">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Give me a reason why you published Gillian Kendall&rsquo;s &ldquo;<a href="/article/4724">Easily Led</a>&rdquo; [November 2012]. Give me a reason for not canceling my subscription. Her essay is well written but trite, narcissistic, and vapid. The sex scenes are not the problem. The problem is simply the emptiness of it, eight pages of beautifully written nothingness &mdash; like the rainbow that reveals itself in the skin of a dead mackerel or a puddle of motor oil. If this is where <em>The Sun</em> is heading, then count me out.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Daniel T. Weaver<br>Amsterdam, New York</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="395">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>What bothers me the most about Gillian Kendall&rsquo;s &ldquo;Easily Led&rdquo; is that men like Nelson, who refuse to be monogamous, seem to have a special power over women. Many times I&rsquo;ve wondered how these women can endure, much less enjoy, playing second fiddle to another.</p>

<p>It bothers me not only because I definitely do not have that power but also because, the few times I have had the opportunity to be unfaithful, I have denied myself the quick and easy pleasure because it doesn&rsquo;t sit well with my conscience. The reward for my choice never comes, however. I write this alone in my house in the woods. Why am I perpetually single while less-ethical men seem to find love so easily and so frequently?</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Kyle<br>Enosburg, Vermont</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="396">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I love a good love story, and Gillian Kendall&rsquo;s &ldquo;Easily Led&rdquo; is among the best I&rsquo;ve read. That it&rsquo;s a true story rather than fiction makes it even better. It reminds us that a love some would consider wrong can be even more right than the socially acceptable kind. Renegade love can feed our soul and transform our deepest self.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Lois Latman<br>Lake Worth, Florida</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="397">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Gillian Kendall&rsquo;s compassion, intellect, and brutal honesty give hope to those of us over fifty who also wish someday to reach our &ldquo;wise old crone&rdquo; stage of femininity. Her essay &ldquo;Easily Led&rdquo; delivered a double whammy: the knowledge that most of us spend our lives trying to re-create our first great love; and that, even thirty-five years and thirty pounds later, we are still capable of the miraculous psychosis known as &ldquo;the real thing.&rdquo;</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Mary Rogalski<br>Glendale, Arizona</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

